<li id="cite_note-73"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-73">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>Euboulos</i> may be a cult title here and not the name of the god Eubuleus; elsewhere it is an epithet of the sea god <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nereus" title="Nereus">Nereus</a>, perfect in his knowledge of truth and justice, and in his own Orphic hymn the guardian of the "roots" of the sea. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pindar" title="Pindar">Pindar</a>, <i>Pythian Ode</i> 3.93; Hesiod, <i>Theogony</i> 233–236; <i>Orphic Hymn</i> 23; Athanassakis, <i>Hesiod</i>, p. 52; Pierre Bonnechere, "Trophonius of Lebadea: Mystery Aspects of an Oracular Cult in Boeotia," in <i>Greek Mysteries: The Archaeology and Ritual of Ancient Greek Secret Cults</i> (Routledge, 2003, 2005), p. 188.</span>
