<li id="cite_note-163"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-163">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Van Amersfoort, "Traces of an Alexandrian Orphic Theogony," pp. 16–17.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-164"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-164">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Van Amersfoort, "Traces of an Alexandrian Orphic Theogony," pp. 17–18. Betegh, <i>The Derveni Papyrus</i>, p. 151, summarizes this version as follows: "The story starts with Chaos; then comes the egg; the bottom part of the egg submerges and becomes Pluton, and Kronos — not a separate god but identified with <a href="Chronos" title="Chronos">Chronos</a> — swallows this heavy matter. The middle part, covering the first sediment, becomes Poseidon. The upper part of the egg, being purer and lighter, fiery in nature, goes upward and is called Zeus, and so forth."</span>
</li>
