<li id="cite_note-194"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-194">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dante" class="mw-redirect" title="Dante">Dante</a>, <i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inferno_(Dante)" title="Inferno (Dante)">Inferno</a></i>, Canto VII.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-195"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-195">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">For instance, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Bondanella" title="Peter Bondanella">Peter Bondanella</a> in his note to the translation of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Wadsworth_Longfellow" title="Henry Wadsworth Longfellow">Henry Wadsworth Longfellow</a>, <i>The Inferno: Dante Alighieri</i> (Barnes &amp; Noble Classics, 2003), pp. 202–203. Dante may simply be preserving the longstanding conflation of Greek <i>Plouton</i> and <i>Ploutos</i>; see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allen_Mandelbaum" title="Allen Mandelbaum">Allen Mandelbaum</a>, note to his translation of <i>The Divine Comedy of Dante Alighieri: Inferno</i> (Bantam Dell, 2004, originally published 1980), p. 357. In modern Italian, the name of the classical ruler of the underworld is <i>Plutone</i>.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-196"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="Pluto_(mythology)#cite_ref-196">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The tormented souls wail <i>"Perché tieni? e "Perché burli?"</i> ("'Why do you hoard?' 'Why do you squander?'"): <i>Inferno</i>, Canto VII, line 30.</span>
